(1345, 235, '_designs_block_block-_crb_subcontent_0', 'Another outstanding feature of those years’ design is the furniture on thin legs, as it makes it look graceful and almost soaring above the floor. Each and every interior’s style and trend is known for its colors and textures. The 50’s style is famous for its bright and colorful shades. The room, designed to the 50’s standards, has to be of rich and saturated colors. The bravest combinations are playing the main role in the design, as orange, blue, dark brown, and red are mixed with the pastel shades. Different graphic prints are also often used to make the colors look even more emphatic. Lights were of specific importance in the 50’s style designs, that is why so many torcheres and lamps with exquisite abat-jours can be found in the rooms. It is such illumination that makes it for the warm, cosy and romantic atmosphere in the flat. Such intricate and daedal patterns as flowers, geometrical figures and ornaments are also a sign of the 50’s style. They create a certain sentimentality of the apartment. The 50’s designers were not ashamed of substitutes and imitations, therefore plastic, plywood, monochromatic upholstery and metal elements were widely used in the interiors of the time. But it was the glossy surfaces that were a real bombshell - stylish, convenient and affordable. Carpet flooring and colorful ceramic tiles, laid in chess way, also got its share in the style’s popularity. The Zeitgeist can best be seen in small details. Home décor of the 50’s is all about coziness and warmth of the interior, that is why retro style is famous for its outlandish and bright items. Those can be hand painted plates of a special style, crystal vases, photos in wooden picture frames, old-fashioned telephones, posters, and old cup sets. Automobile industry of the 50’s was growing rapidly, so even the look of the household appliances and some décor elements resembles the style of the most famous car brands, while transducers, levers and other details of the household devices look like information panels.'),
