(5026, 708, '_designs_block_block-_crb_row_images_1_image-_crb_d_image_0', '710'),
(5027, 708, '_designs_block_block-_crb_row_images_sources_1_link-_crb_image_link_0', 'www.lemamobili.com'),
(5028, 708, '_designs_block_block-_crb_row_images_sources_1_link-_crb_image_link_1', 'www.muuto.com'),
(5029, 708, '_designs_block_block-_crb_row_images_sources_1_link-_crb_image_link_2', 'blog.urbanoutfitters.com'),
(5030, 708, '_designs_block_block-_crb_row_images_sources_1_link-_crb_image_link_3', 'casalinga.dk'),
(5031, 708, '_designs_block_block-_crb_subcontent_1', '<p style="text-align: center;">#workspace #office # workroom #workplace #furniture #style #blue #plant #light #nature #interior #design #architecture #Muuto #LemaMobili #spacefilling</p>\r\n<p>The design of the working space can make you happy !</p>\r\n<p>Colour is one of the strongest means of influencing the working mood. How do you choose the colour you need among the whole colour palette ?</p>\r\n<p>First of all, some colours are more favourable for work : it is white (purity), grey (in combination with white and with bright accents), warm shades (cosiness), sky-blue and dark blue (it tones up, refreshes, fosters concentration), green (calms down, relaxes), and bright colours in small quantities. Do not forget, however, that an excessive presence of one colour is not pleasant and monotonous, in particular for work. Therefore, any colour should be diluted. For a fresh mood and atmosphere, you may add small accents with nature motives – textured wall paper or colour prints, accessories, paintings.</p>'),
